    "description": "Poet, calligrapher, and Chan (Zen) Buddhist adept, Huang Tingjian believed that calligraphy should be spontaneous and self-expressive\u2014\u201ca picture of the mind.\u201d Containing nearly twelve hundred characters, this handscroll is a master\u00adpiece of cursive-script writing. It transcribes an account of a rivalry between two officials: Lian Po, a distinguished general; and Lin Xiangru, a skilled strategist. Huang\u2019s transcription ends abruptly with Lin\u2019s words: \u201cWhen two tigers fight, one must perish. I behave as I do because I put our country\u2019s fate before private feuds.\u201d Read in the context of Song political infighting, Huang\u2019s transcription becomes a powerful indictment of the partisanship that led to his own banishment in 1094.",
